# **1\. PRODUCT-BRAND ALIGNMENT**

## **MVB Purpose**

This document connects your PRD's product strategy to brand execution. Every brand decision supports a product need. Every product moment reinforces the brand. This isn't decoration‚Äîit's strategy.

## **Problem ‚Üí Solution ‚Üí Brand**

### **THE PROBLEM (From PRD)**

**User:** "Powerless Scroller" \- Gen Z/Millennials who've tried Screen Time limits but always click "Ignore"

**Behavior:** Opening TikTok/Instagram on autopilot, losing 3.5+ hours/week to doomscrolling, they never intended

**Emotion:** Shame about lack of self-control, frustration that nothing works, desire for external enforcement

### **OUR SOLUTION (Product \+ Brand)**

**Product:** iOS-enforced time-trading‚Äîearn productive time by using other productive apps instead (Duolingo, Kindle, etc.), unlock vice apps with time earned , can't bypass

**Brand:** Supportive accountability buddy (Clepsy) that makes enforcement feel collaborative, not punitive

**Outcome:** Break autopilot habit, transform leisure from shame to earned reward, 50% reduction in unintentional usage

## **How Brand Serves Product Strategy**

| Product Need (PRD Goal) | Brand Solution |
| ----- | ----- |
| **Break autopilot habit** (force conscious decisions) | Shield screen with Clepsy character breaks pattern, shows exact time needed, uses warm supportive copy |
| **Reduce shame** (users already feel bad) | Supportive tone: "Let's do this together" not "You failed again." Clepsy is patient, not judgmental |
| **Drive retention** (25% Day-30 target) | Character creates emotional connection. Celebrating character on milestones \= positive reinforcement loop |
| **Visualize balance** (make time-trading concrete) | Hourglass character's sand level \= user's balance. Functional data visualization with personality |
| **Justify enforcement** (iOS blocks are harsh) | Character softens the "no" with empathy. "Build 23 more minutes" feels collaborative not punitive |

# **2\. CHARACTER PSYCHOLOGY & STORY**

## **Why Clepsy Exists**

Users need external enforcement but hate being controlled. Clepsy solves this: a buddy who enforces rules *with* you, not *on* you. The hourglass body isn't decorative‚Äîit's functional balance visualization. Every character state matches a product moment.

## **The Name & Origin**

**Clepsy** from *clepsydra* (ancient Greek: Œ∫ŒªŒµœàœçŒ¥œÅŒ±) \= "time thief" ‚Äî literally "stealer of water/time"

**Narrative:** Doomscrolling apps are the modern time thieves stealing hours from your life. Clepsy helps you steal your time back. The character uses an hourglass to track stolen time and help you reclaim it.

## **Character Design Rationale**

### **Why Hourglass Body?**

* **Functional:** Sand level \= user's balance (data viz)  
* **Universal:** ‚è≥ recognized globally as "time"  
* **Unique:** No competitor has hourglass character  
* **Narrative:** Ties to "time thief" story perfectly  
* **Scalable:** Works at any size, always readable

### **Why Personality?**

* Softens iOS enforcement (feels collaborative)  
* Creates emotional connection (retention)  
* Makes abstract concrete (time \= sand visual)  
* Differentiates from cold tech (warm buddy)  
* Enables tone consistency (character \= voice)

## **Character States Mapped to Product Moments**

### **1\. DEFAULT / PATIENT (üòä)**

**Product Context:** Shield screens, dashboard, waiting states **When Used:** User tries to open TikTok. Balance too low. **User Emotion:** Frustrated, might feel shame **Brand Role:** Clepsy appears calm, patient: "Gain minutes to unlock." No judgment, just facts. **Psychology:** Neutral expression prevents rage-quit while maintaining boundary

### **2\. ENCOURAGING (üòÑ)**

**Product Context:** Milestone notifications, earning time **When Used:** User hits 15-min earning milestone **User Emotion:** Needs positive reinforcement **Brand Role:** Clepsy celebrates: "Nice\! You just earned 15 minutes. Keep it up\!" **Psychology:** Dopamine hit, motivation to continue earning

### **3\. CELEBRATING (üéâ)**

**Product Context:** Achievements, streaks, big milestones **When Used:** 7-day streak achieved **User Emotion:** Pride, accomplishment **Brand Role:** Clepsy throws celebration: "7 Day Streak\! You're building a real habit here." **Psychology:** Validates effort, reinforces behavior change

## **Character Behavior Rules**

1. **Sand level always reflects balance:** Top bulb fills when earning, drains when spending. User can see their "account" status instantly.

2. **Expression matches context:** Patient when blocking, encouraging when earning, celebrating on achievements. Wrong expression \= confusing UX.

3. **Always present on key screens:** Shield screen (largest), dashboard (hero), notifications (icon). Character \= accountability buddy, must be visible.

4. **Subtle animation only:** Gentle float (3-4s loop). No bouncing, spinning, or distracting motion that breaks iOS calm aesthetic.

## **Character Design Specs**

**Visual Elements:**

* Hourglass body (two bulbs connected)

**Functional Behavior:**

* Sand level reflects user's balance  
* Top bulb fills when earning  
* Sand drains when spending  
* Expression changes with context  
* Always visible on key screens  
* Floats (subtle animation)

# **3\. BRAND IN USER JOURNEY (PRD MAPPED)**

Every PRD user journey has brand touchpoints. This section maps product flows to brand implementation‚Äîshowing exactly where brand appears and why.

## **JOURNEY 1: Onboarding \- First-Time Setup**

**PRD Goal:** User understands time-trading, grants permissions, selects apps (P0)

**Brand Touchpoint:** Clepsy introduces concept **Character State:** Default/friendly **Copy Example:** "Hi\! I'm Clepsy. I help you earn your scrolling time by tracking productive activities. Let's set up your vice apps to block and productive apps to track." **Why This Matters:** First impression. Character establishes supportive tone from start. User meets their "buddy."

## **JOURNEY 2: Earning Time \- Productive Session**

**PRD Goal:** Passive tracking in background, milestone notifications (P0)

**Brand Touchpoint:** Milestone notification **Character State:** Encouraging (üòÑ) **Copy Example:** "üéâ Nice\! You just earned 15 minutes. Keep it up\! Balance: 38 minutes" **Why This Matters:** Positive reinforcement loop. Dopamine hit \= motivation to continue. Character celebrates *with* user.

## **JOURNEY 3: Shield Screen \- Attempting to Open Vice App (The Block)**

**PRD Goal:** Break autopilot habit, force conscious decision (P0 \- core value prop)

**Brand Touchpoint:** Shield screen with character **Character State:** Patient (üòä) **Visual:** Clepsy large, sand level shown, balance displayed **Copy Example:** "Earn productivity minutes to unlock TikTok" \+ "You've earned 12 min today" **Why This Matters:** CRITICAL MOMENT. User opened TikTok on autopilot. Clepsy breaks pattern with empathy, not judgment. Shows exact requirement. Character softens enforcement.

## **JOURNEY 4: Unlocking \- Claiming Earned Time**

**PRD Goal:** Feel like fair transaction, guilt-free enjoyment (P0 \- "Steroid" value prop)

**Brand Touchpoint:** Unlock confirmation **Character State:** Encouraging **Copy Example:** "‚úì TikTok unlocked\! You've earned this. Enjoy your 23 minutes." **Why This Matters:** Removes guilt. User EARNED this time. Character affirms transaction. Makes leisure feel rewarding, not shameful.

## **JOURNEY 5: Low Balance Warning \- Time Running Out**

**PRD Goal:** Real-time deduction, re-shield when balance hits zero (P0)

**Brand Touchpoint:** Notification 5 min before time's up **Character State:** Default/gentle **Copy Example:** "‚è∞ Heads up: You've got 5 minutes left on TikTok. Wrap up soon, or earn more." **Why This Matters:** Gentle warning, not harsh alarm. Offers solution. Respects user autonomy. Character \= helpful buddy, not enforcer.

## **JOURNEY 6: Achievement \- 7-Day Streak**

**PRD Goal:** Drive retention (25% Day-30), build habit formation

**Brand Touchpoint:** Achievement notification \+ in-app celebration **Character State:** Celebrating (üéâ) **Copy Example:** "üî• 7 Day Streak\! You've earned time every day this week. You're building a real habit here." **Why This Matters:** Names the achievement (habit-building). Character shares pride. Drives continued engagement.

# **4\. IOS VISUAL DESIGN SYSTEM**

## **iOS-First Design Philosophy**

We follow Apple's Human Interface Guidelines while maintaining brand distinctiveness. SF Pro typography, 8pt grid spacing, native animations, dark mode primary. Every choice optimized for iOS.

## **Color System**

### **Primary Colors**

**Midnight Blue (\#1E2A3A)**

* Usage: Primary background  
* Purpose: App background, creates calm/trust  
* Psychology: Dark background reduces eye strain for night scrolling

**Sand Gold (\#F4A259)**

* Usage: Primary accent, CTAs, earned time, sand  
* Purpose: Draws attention, positive association  
* Psychology: Warm, rewarding, differentiates from cold productivity apps

**Hourglass Brown (\#8B6F47)**

* Usage: Character frame, warm accents  
* Purpose: Character identity, organic warmth  
* Psychology: Trustworthy, grounded, approachable

### **Functional Colors**

**Accent Teal (\#4ECDC4)**

* Usage: Success states, earning indicators  
* Purpose: Positive reinforcement  
* Psychology: Progress, achievement, growth

**Warning Orange (\#FF8C42)**

* Usage: Spending, low balance, alerts  
* Purpose: Draw attention without alarm  
* Psychology: Caution without panic

**Surface (\#2A3B4D)**

* Usage: Cards, elevated elements  
* Purpose: Depth hierarchy  
* Psychology: Organization, structure

### **Swift Color Extensions**

```
// Color extensions for Clepsy brand
extension Color {
    static let clepsyMidnight = Color(hex: "1E2A3A")
    static let clepsySurface = Color(hex: "2A3B4D")
    static let clepsyGold = Color(hex: "F4A259")
    static let clepsyBrown = Color(hex: "8B6F47")
    static let clepsyTeal = Color(hex: "4ECDC4")
    static let clepsyOrange = Color(hex: "FF8C42")
    
    static let textPrimary = Color(hex: "F9F6F0")
    static let textSecondary = Color(hex: "D4CFC4")
}
```

## **Typography (SF Pro)**

### **Font Hierarchy**

| Use Case | Font Variant | Size | Weight | Why |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Large Title (Dashboard) | SF Pro Display | 34pt | Bold | iOS native, maximum impact |
| Headings | SF Pro Display | 28pt / 22pt | Semibold | Clear hierarchy, readable |
| Body Text | SF Pro Text | 17pt | Regular | Optimized for reading, iOS default |
| Buttons / CTAs | SF Pro Rounded | 17pt | Semibold | Friendly, approachable for actions |
| Metadata / Labels | SF Pro Text | 15pt | Regular | Clear at small sizes |

### **Swift Typography Extensions**

```
// Typography extensions
extension Font {
    static let clepsyTitle = Font.system(.largeTitle, design: .default, weight: .bold)
    static let clepsyHeading = Font.system(.title2, design: .default, weight: .semibold)
    static let clepsyBody = Font.system(.body, design: .default)
    static let clepsyCTA = Font.system(.body, design: .rounded, weight: .semibold)
    static let clepsyCaption = Font.system(.subheadline, design: .default)
}
```

### **Why SF Pro Over Custom Fonts?**

* Zero web font loading (instant)  
* Optimized for iOS screens  
* Accessibility built-in (dynamic type support)  
* Feels native/trustworthy  
* Three variants (Display, Text, Rounded) for hierarchy  
* Custom fonts add 200-500kb, require loading state, don't support all iOS accessibility features

## **Spacing (8pt Grid)**

### **iOS Spacing Scale**

* **8pt (--space-1):** Tight spacing, inline elements  
* **16pt (--space-2):** Standard spacing between elements  
* **24pt (--space-3):** Section spacing, card padding  
* **32pt (--space-4):** Large spacing, screen margins  
* **40pt (--space-5):** Extra large spacing  
* **48pt (--space-6):** Maximum spacing, sections

### **Touch Targets (iOS HIG)**

* **Minimum:** 44pt √ó 44pt (iOS HIG requirement)  
* **Primary CTAs:** 48pt height minimum  
* **Icons:** 24pt √ó 24pt with 44pt tap area  
* **List items:** 48pt minimum height  
* **Spacing between tappable:** 8pt minimum

## **Animations (iOS Native)**

### **Animation Guidelines**

* Use iOS spring curves for natural feel  
* Keep animations under 0.4s (feels responsive)  
* Character float: 3-4s loop, subtle (10pt movement)  
* Button interactions: 0.2s spring  
* Sheet presentations: 0.3s ease-in-out

### **SwiftUI Animation Code example**

```
// iOS-native animation curves
.animation(.spring(response: 0.3, dampingFraction: 0.7))  // Bouncy
.animation(.easeInOut(duration: 0.25))  // Smooth
.animation(.easeOut(duration: 0.2))  // Quick exit

// Character float animation
@State private var isFloating = false

.offset(y: isFloating ? -10 : 0)
.animation(
    Animation.easeInOut(duration: 3)
        .repeatForever(autoreverses: true),
    value: isFloating
)
.onAppear { isFloating = true }
```

# **5\. TONE & VOICE GUIDELINES**

## **Voice Principles**

### **‚úì We Sound Like**

Encouraging ‚Ä¢ Direct ‚Ä¢ Honest ‚Ä¢ Empathetic ‚Ä¢ Patient ‚Ä¢ Celebrating wins ‚Ä¢ Acknowledging struggle ‚Ä¢ "We're doing this together"

### **‚úó We Don't Sound Like**

Shaming ‚Ä¢ Guilt-tripping ‚Ä¢ Preachy ‚Ä¢ Condescending ‚Ä¢ Therapy-speak ‚Ä¢ Overly cute/childish ‚Ä¢ Harsh enforcement ‚Ä¢ "You failed again"

## **Copy Framework by Context**

| Context | User State | Copy Example | Why It Works |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Shield Screen** | Frustrated, blocked | "Earn productivity minutes to unlock TikTok" | Direct, shows exact need, no shame |
| **Milestone** | Needs reinforcement | "Nice\! You just earned 15 minutes. Keep it up\!" | Celebrates without patronizing |
| **Low Balance** | Needs gentle warning | "Heads up: 5 minutes left. Wrap up soon, or earn more." | Gentle, offers solution, respects autonomy |
| **Zero Balance** | Out of time | "That's all for now. Ready to earn more?" | Patient, forward-looking, no judgment |
| **Unlock Success** | Claiming reward | "‚úì TikTok unlocked\! You've earned this. Enjoy your 23 minutes." | Affirms earning, guilt-free permission |
| **Achievement** | Pride, accomplishment | "üî• 7 Day Streak\! You're building a real habit here." | Names achievement, genuine celebration |

## **Detailed Voice Rules**

### **1\. Be Specific with Time**

* **Good:** "23 minutes"  
* **Bad:** "some time"  
* **Why:** Shows respect for user's effort

### **2\. Acknowledge Progress**

* **Good:** "You've earned 12 min today"  
* **Bad:** "You don't have enough time"  
* **Why:** Reminds them they're making progress even when blocked

### **3\. Always Offer Solution**

* **Good:** "Wrap up soon, or earn more"  
* **Bad:** "Time's almost up"  
* **Why:** Gives user agency, next step clear

### **4\. Use "You've Earned"**

* **Good:** "You've earned this"  
* **Bad:** "You can have this"  
* **Why:** Reinforces exchange, not permission

### **5\. Avoid Therapy Words**

* **Bad:** "mindfulness," "self-care," "journey"  
* **Good:** Keep it practical  
* **Why:** Users want accountability, not therapy
